<br>
Mages, have there been any further adjustments to the pet on test? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zarbonius>Zarbonius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 223<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/4/03 5:22 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: After all this</span><hr size=1> ...so I figured I'd head over to the Mage board for a bit to discuss this whole &quot;fire pet&quot; thing with them.  I think a lot of the initial excitement over this has worn down, and the majority of the mages that posted were very reasonable and interested in making the pet balanced as well as useful.<br>
<br>
In any case, I came away from the discussion with the following model of a fire pet in my mind.  It looks to me as though it fulfills most of the requirements of both classes, but then, I'm a bit biased.  Take a gander, and poke a few holes in it where you see 'em:<br>
<br>
**Disclaimer**  -  All proposed characteristics are aimed at the level 63 spell pet, which is a level 60 NPC, and casts up to level 52 spells.  The same general standards would apply to the lesser pets, with modifications where appropriate.<br>
<br>
<br>
Proposed Fire Pet characteristics:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet does not melee whatsoever<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet stands by the mage's side, and upon /pet attack, either chain-casts, or casts at fairly regular intervals<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>3)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet's nukes get an inherent resist modifier, similar to our post-60 draughts (somewhere in the range of -50) <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>4)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet casts wizard spells, but a limited selection of them<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>5)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet has an infinite mana pool <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>6)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  After each cast, the pet is stunned for a fixed amount of time (~3-5 seconds)<br>
<br>
<br>
Ok, a couple of these might look controversial at first glance, so I'm going to discuss the reasoning behind them briefly.   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1)  No melee </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->- hey, it's a wizard.  It should have the melee skills of a cotton ball.  Give it a beer mug and a glowing ring or something to emphasize that this pet does damage exclusively through spells.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2)  Pet doesn't move (much)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - In order to make the pet act more like the wizard it claims to be, it should be standing back from the mob (much like the mage is) and nuking from afar.  It should follow the mage as other pets do, but upon /pet attack, it should plant itself firmly and start chaining spells at its target.  This should allow the mage to position the pet appropriately, yet still be able to move it out of AEs on raids when necessary (with a little bit of work).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>3) Inherent Resist Modifier</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - Mages are (understandably) concerned about the pet's spells simply being resisted left, right, and center, thereby dropping the pet's utility to near zero in some cases.  The pet is a level 60 caster, and will likely be used on targets ranging from level ~59 to 70+.  Resists are heavily dependent on relative level, so a resist modifier would likely be in order.  With an inherent -50 resist modifier (akin to our post-60 Draughts) on all of its nukes, the pet should be useful on high level (70+) raid mobs, as they will be heavily debuffed, and most of its spells should land fairly well.  In XP groups, the -50 modifier will allow the pet to land nukes fairly reliably (without requiring the mage to Malosinia each target) against mobs that XP groups will likely be fighting (in the ~59-65 range), but with occasional resists, as the pet is level 60, casting against mobs a few levels below it up to 5+ levels higher than it.  **Note** if SOE does follow through and make spell damage (including pet spell damage) viewable by everyone on live servers, then parsing the pet's DPS will be MUCH easier.  (at the very least, they should at least let the mage see the pet's spell damage)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>4)  Limited selection of spells</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - the pet should not be casting spells like Markar's Clash (it won't stun mobs at that level anyway) or cancel magic, and probably not snare or root.  It is supposed to be a means of ranged DPS, and the pet AI is inadequate to make appropriate use of the &quot;utility&quot; spells, so it should be limited to straight nukes.  Rend, Conflag, Force Strike, and Draught of Fire should be a sufficient selection for the pet to clearly have a wizard &quot;flavour&quot; and accomplish its DPS goals without stepping too heavily on Wizard toes.   Self buffs can of course include Arch Shielding, and either Diamondskin or Steelskin and possibly the FR/CR &amp; DR/PR buffs.  Hopefully the Pet AI will be smart enough to only cast those buffs when not engaged in combat, and not re-cast them unnecessarily.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>5)  Infinite Mana pool</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - If SOE attempts to limit the pet's DPS by tweaking the size of its mana pool, mages will find a way around the limitation - they're clever like we are <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  From reclaiming/chaining to suspending/switching to alternate pet, a manapool-based DPS limit on the pet is extremely unlikely to accomplish its goal while still leaving the pet actually useful to the Mage.  The more complex the mana-system that SOE implements, the more likely it is that mages will find a way around it.  K.I.S.S. and avoid a whole lot of potential problems.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>6)  Self-Stun Effect</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - An NPC casting wizard spells on an infinite manapool, and ignoring recast times completely (as NPCs and pets are wont to do) would be capable of some outlandish DPS, and a fire pet doing so would be unbalanced.  In order to limit the pet's chain-casting ability, I would propose that the pet be stunned after each cast for a period of ~3-5 seconds (exact time would depend on tuning/testing).  This is a method of both ensuring that the pet observes at least the mandatory recast time, and also artificially decreases the pet's DPS without touching the cast times of the spells themselves.  If you're in a roleplaying mood, one could also say that the pet casts a mini-Harvest spell after each nuke - explaining both the infinite manapool as well as the stun effect.<br>
<br>
<br>
The combined effect of these changes is a fire pet that should be manageable/useful on raids, useful but not overpowered in XP groups, has tuneable DPS (via the length of the stun component), doesn't intrude heavily on Wizard territory in terms of burst DPS, Lures, or certain unnamed &quot;signature spells&quot;, and provides fairly reliable, constant DPS that is comparable to but does not exceed that of the other mage pets.<br>
<br>
<br>
Potential problems I see so far include:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>a)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet (as outlined above) doesn't have to be buffed like other pets do, and can essentially run forever without being buffed.  Not a *major* issue, but could probably be solved by creating a specific buff for the fire pet that would have to be refreshed occasionally to keep it operating at max DPS.  (perhaps some sort of fire-pet-only spell haste buff, without which its casting time would be 50% greater than normal).<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>b)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet *is* a wizard-class pet, and mages have received abilities outside their class via their pets before.  As such, there *may* be sufficient precedent to allow it to cast a cold-based nuke.  IMHO Frozen Harpoon should be the nuke of choice, as it is of a comparable size to the other above-listed nukes, and as only 1 of 5 nukes in the pet's lineup, won't significantly add to the Mage class's ability to damage high FR mobs.  One caveat - Frozen Harpoon is quested, and the quest is a bit of a pain (but not extraordinarily difficult by any means), so some may object to it being given away freely to a pet.  Personally, if an ice nuke *had* to be given to the pet, I wouldn't have a problem if it were Frozen Harpoon.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>c)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The pet's level (60), along with the -50 resist modifier on its nukes, may allow it to land DDs on extremely resistant mobs (eg. reavers, etc.), which have traditionally only been DD-able by Wizards.  Then again, it is unlikely that the pet will be able to land its nukes very often or for full damage, so our titles as &quot;Lure-bearers&quot; should be secure.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>d)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  An infinite mana pool may be unacceptable to some - in that case, a very large, but finite pool could be implemented in place of the &quot;required&quot; spell-haste buff proposed above.  Either solution would require the mage to expend mana occasionally to keep the pet operating at its full potential.  Alternatively the pet could have a reasonably sized mana pool (~3k-ish), and it could actually cast a mini-Harvest after each nuke.  This mini-Harvest would leave it stunned, and would replace perhaps 60-70% of the average mana cost of the pet's nukes (perhaps ~170-180 mana as pets don't have spec savings AFAIK) .  As such, the pet would eventually run OOM, and either have to med or be reclaimed/recast, but it would be able to sustain its ~70 DPS for a reasonable length of time before running out of mana (reasonable when compared to the other mage pets, that is).<br>
<br>
<br>
Ok, that's pretty much my concept of what could be an acceptable solution to the &quot;fire pet issue&quot;.  There's not a whole lot that's really new here - I just thought I'd assemble it into one relatively coherent post.  Let me know what you think, and also if you see anything here that could be abused/exploited, or strikes you as just plain wrong.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bodithegnome>Bodi The Gnome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/4/03 5:25 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: After all this</span><hr size=1> It's an unorthodox pet thus far, because our new fire pet is chain stun or chain root.  I like it.<br>
<br>
Well look at it this way Wizards: You can still outnuke Magicians and their pet <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
