 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zarbonius>Zarbonius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 224<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/03 2:48 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: *FACTS* on new mage pets</span><hr size=1> Qaman,<br>
<br>
Your wording could imply something that I don't think you actually were saying, but just to clarify, I wasn't suggesting giving them the actual post-60 Draughts with the -50 modifier on them.  I only meant that they could cast the spells I listed, but receive a resist modifier on them that was about -50 or so.  Sort of an inherent &quot;pet-nuke modifier&quot;.<br>
<br>
To be honest, initially I wasn't terribly wild about the resist modifier idea either. The considerations that I took into account (as listed above) were:<br>
<br>
1)  The Fire pet really should be able to hit raid targets, and I'm not sure that what is effectively a level 60 caster would be able to land regular nukes against a level 70+ target, even after all debuffs have been landed.<br>
<br>
2)  The Fire pet should probably be able to do its DPS reasonably well against appropriately-leveled targets in an XP group without special debuffing, somewhat similarly to the other Mage pets.  Its DPS should be tuned via spell selection and the self-stun listed above, so factoring in resists as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>major</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> method of DPS control would probably be excessive.  Besides, for resistant mobs, the pet would probably get a fair number of resists even with the -50 modifier, especially if the mob was higher than level 60.<br>
<br>
Put those two together, and there is a bit of a problem.  The resist modifier was a solution that seemed to solve both problems<br>
<br>
I see your point, though - a -50 modifier, when paired with  Malosinia, does seem to give it a bit of an advantage over actual wizards.  Personally, I wouldn't be *too* upset about that, as I don't believe most Mages in XP groups would want to cast Malosinia on each target, so the advantage isn't as great as it might first appear.  Besides, it would only allow the pet to, at best, reach its target DPS, not exceed it, as DPS would already be tuned and limited by the other means I proposed.  This is also a bit of a compromise on the Lure issue, as my proposal does not give the pet any true Lure spells, or even Enticement of Flame.  (and yes, I know &quot;compromise&quot; is just another way of saying &quot;a solution that ultimately pleases nobody&quot;. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      <br>
<br>
Anyway, got any ideas on how to accomplish both 1) and 2) without resorting to a resist modifier?  I'm just spitballing some ideas here, so it's not like I'm married to the idea of a resist modifier.  That being said, I really think that case 1) is the most important one, and the one that warrants the resist modifer most, but I think 2) is also a reasonably justifiable case.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Edit - threw in (yet another) qualifying phrase that I had forgotten.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zarbonius>Zarbonius</A> at: 6/5/03 2:53 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=qaman>Qaman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 3449<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/03 2:57 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: *FACTS* on new mage pets</span><hr size=1> &gt;1) The Fire pet really should be able to hit raid targets, and I'm not sure that what is effectively a level 60 caster would be able to land regular nukes against a level 70+ target, even after all debuffs have been landed.<br>
<br>
I am not sure this is actually a problem though, as it is still an NPC. NPCs have slightly different rules for landing spells than PCs do. In addition, the other pets would presumably suffer from exactly the same problem with regards to melee and spell damage.<br>
<br>
&gt;Anyway, got any ideas on how to accomplish both 1) and 2) without resorting to a resist modifier?<br>
<br>
If it is actually a real problem, they could probably do something like adding an 'effective casting level' buff to Burnout. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4380">Qaman</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
